{{notability|date=September 2012}}
'''Gladvertising''' (n) is [[outdoor advertising]] that uses cameras and [[facial recognition software]] to read a consumer's [[mood (psychology)|mood]], then pushes products relevant to the target [[emotional state]].<ref>{{citation|author=Keats, Jonathan|url=https://www.wired.com/magazine/2011/06/st_jw_gladvertising/|title=Jargon Watch|work=Wired Magazine|date=July 2011|page= 48}}</ref> It uses [[emotion recognition]] software to tailor outdoor adverts to consumers' mood.<ref>{{citation|url=http://jazarah.net/the-real-minority-report-gladvertising-kick-starts-revolution-in-outdoor-advertising/|title=The real Minority Report: "Gladvertising" kick starts revolution in outdoor advertising|work=jazarah.net|date=February 28, 2011}}</ref>
The terms was coined in a July 2011 report by the Centre of Future Studies<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.3mgtg.com/PDF/3MGTG_Up_Front_and_Personal_Report.pdf | title=Up Front and Personal Digital Out-Of-Home Communications | publisher=Centre of Future Studies | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110409070651/http://www.3mgtg.com/PDF/3MGTG_Up_Front_and_Personal_Report.pdf | archivedate=April 9, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.futurestudies.co.uk/home.htm|title=Futurist Think Tank & Strategic Futures Consultants: The centre for future studies|publisher=futurestudies.co.uk}}</ref> which suggests that advertisements like the ones in the film ''[[Minority Report (film)|Minority Report]]'' may be well on the way, and indeed, that some already exist. Their report – commissioned by 3MGTG, which specialises in digital advertising – foresees the first step to be advertisements that adapt to our moods.
The technology has been dubbed 'Gladverts' by the report's authors.<ref>{{citation|url=http://technologyinf.com/electronics/minority-report-like-adverts/|title=Minority Report-like adverts|work=www.technologyinf.com|date=June 18, 2011}}</ref>
